    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. if i decide to switch him to a more senior specific food that's lower in fat, is there anything else i should look out for in the ingredients? like specific types of fiber or fats that help with older dogs? i just wanna make sure i'm not missing anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When switching to a senior, lower-fat formula, look for ingredients that support joint health and digestive comfort. Ingredients like glucosamine, chondroitin, and omega-3 fatty acids (like EPA/DHA from fish oil) are excellent additions for joint support. Also, beneficial fibers, such as prebiotics or specific vegetable fibers, can help maintain healthy digestion as seniors sometimes slow down.",
      "source": "target",
